==Description==
{{Blurimage|file=Roadening.png|caption=Housing.}}
The vast landscape of concrete, urban hellscape superimposed on the atmospheric beauty; from the sky to the light, each fragment of the grander picture coalesces to form <span class="level-name>Strums of Suburbia</span> (Level 79). Elevated, sometimes rugged terrain shapes the island; terrain lined by buildings strewn across its surface, occasionally broken up by uniform, precise distribution in plots. In spite of it, human-made adornments and structures—such as hanging lanterns, flags, and street art—break the symmetry, giving the lifeless, towering buildings a sense of humanity. The roads and sidewalks are of asphalt, seemingly haphazardly thrown together, crackable, and painted with haste, yet despite this, they teeter—they sprawl from the ground beneath, they constantly extend and form paths around the artificial, as though water spreading through a maze.
{{Blurimage|file=L-100 Central Road.png|caption=The Central Road.}}
<br>
In the dead center of the level lies a pathway, cleanly carving through buildings and connecting the north and south extremes through one road. Most structures are located nearby, ever-expanding, spreading like a cancer from the very sides of the central road into what lies beyond. Enormous cranes tower over the buildings, each aimlessly weaving and slowly materializing blocks of concrete into rooms precisely attached atop nearby buildings, all while structural support beams stretch and extend upwards to accompany the new foundation. The sidewalks? Populated by utility poles with wires sprouting from their base and cables slowly growing from within others like branches on a tree.
{{Blurimage|file=Interior ho.png|caption=Interior.}}
<br>
Away from the overseeing cranes, near the shore, human construction populates the roads. Primitive, suburban houses of varying styles dwarf the view of the coast, with the occasional greenery filling the corners and cracks of the makeshift paths and sidewalks, greenery no longer repressed by the concrete. Silence permeates the sea's atmosphere, the light from the skybox illuminating and reflecting from it; it sits calmly—devoid of significant waves, absent of movement from below. The civilization beyond the sea, on the "other island" ahead, is the same civilization that stands miles behind you; the level wraps back in on itself seamlessly like an ouroboros, giving it the sense of infinity, each "island" symmetrically placed in a grid.

The interiors of buildings vary, each more disorganized and unrelated than the last. While some rooms possess disconnected, disordered items, nonsensical paintings, and barely recognizable photos, others are instead completely empty, devoid of meaning. The structure of the rooms themselves is chaotic, never too ridiculous to feel implausible, but always disarrayed enough to feel wrong. That disarray leads to the formation of small pockets, walled-off crevices of darkness; that disarray creates paper-thin windows with their otherwise scenic view blocked by walls, or even nothing at all—a hole where a window was meant to be.

Frigid yet pleasant air fills the level, snow seasonally weeps from the abyss above. The sky pulsates, suppressing the daylight’s rebellions, yet that daylight always manages to leave marks of its futile attempts on the surface, and despite the frequently emotionless, bland emptiness that permeates the sky, it's ever-changing, periodically fracturing, unleashing figments of the daylight, letting the battered sun hidden behind pour out its damaged light, casting a weakened, beautiful contrast within the cracks.

=== Locations ===

==== The Radio Field ====
{{Blurimage|file=L-100 Radio Field.png|caption=The overarching field of radio towers.}}
[[File:FTS-Radio tower.ogg|right|300px]]

Away from human reaches, bright red, glimmering lights overlook the distance and stare down, each light piercing through the fog, each light flickering, shining in random patterns. The radio towers stand atop their own miniature island off the coast like kings in a castle, a castle seemingly reserved specifically for them, absent of buildings or cranes. All foreigners who step close feel a palpable, irritating sensation envelope their body with potency, an aggressive reaction to intrusion that grasps and pounds on your chest with ferocity, only made stronger and more unbearable the closer you get. Those close will pass out from the overwhelming sensation; soon after, they go through the same, sped-up decomposition as corpses, leaving no trace behind, almost as if the towers took them somewhere else.

They emit at ever-changing, oscillating frequencies at distances high enough to encapsulate the entire level, and, despite this, the noise they produce stays stagnant, unreactive, and poorly looped, ending abruptly only to come back seconds later. Many describe the noise as ethereal and heavenly—a total contrast to the tower's imposing stature—with a majority finding some solace in it; level-born cultures tend to utilize the sound, whether in their respective folk genres or as a denotation of calmness and peace with the self.

==== Wire Angels ====
{{Blurimage|file=L-100 Wire Angel.png|caption=A Wire Angel formed after the Ruphan independence war.}}
Wire Angels are widely assumed to be natural responses; they're formations reactive to large-scale death commonly caused by conflict. Many cultures view them as a reservoir to commemorate life, each wire interpreted as an effigy-like representation of those who perished in tragedy, an interpretation further invigorated by Wire Angels becoming nonfunctional, the electricity it once produced absent, blocked, as though someone had turned it off, yet the power is still present, trying to escape, thrashing the insides of the utility pole to no response or connection, a prison for it, where it's confined and left to experience its natural course of decay.

