{{Template:Blurimage|file=L-100 Addendum.jpeg|caption=Untitled blog attachment}}
<div class="log-content">
Tantalising cold; It's familiar, never too dissimilar to what I remember—a disconnected mimicry of my memories. A breeze constantly swept by me—the breeze constantly relieved me, reminded me that I'm safer and at some sort of home; yet, the smallest inconsistencies always bugged me: windows misaligned, walls with no purpose, doors where a porch should be; it's like chewing into a soft food and hearing something crunch—yet that crunch feels oddly human, no? I love the unexplainable, eye-candy-like contrast between people and brutalism, especially when decorated by snow or nature; human-made, yet human-hostile, yet human-accustomed; this place rids of the first condition and still feels homely; something that I've been trying to describe for a while but just can't. It's special to me because it's one of ''those'' feelings you can only really resonate with if you grew up with it. And yet, despite the lack of humanity behind these buildings, the splotches of imperfections fool me into believing otherwise.

The permanent night time too; young me always enjoyed wandering the streets at night when I could, looking at the massive, mostly unlit blocks with strewn light posts, absent of sounds that weren't mine, and as an adult now, it's no different. The white snow, the angelic lights, the desaturated blue that coats every surface–it all harmonises; it wraps around from a bitter hostility to an unchanging comfort. You might think I'm insane—I mean, you definitely do—but in my opinion, true beauty is the horseshoe theory. The fact that something can sound so depressing on the surface, yet because of humanity's ability to transform anything into something for us, it becomes beautiful as you look into it; it's the little details, like the random, scrappy, cracked signs or the nationalist graffiti, that make it all stick.

Also, on the topic of people, the drunk motherfuckers on the streets remind me a lot of home; the troglodyte activities and all. Even the pink light through the window in a random room snitching on the fact that the guy is growing drugs; I could probably sit here and write about the random street fights I've seen between teenagers who somehow just have firecrackers all day, and honestly I might see that being entertaining, but philosophical rambling is more my taste, so you're not getting that unless I get reallyyyyy bored.
</div>
<br>
