{{Template:Blurimage|file=L-100-CoastalFracture.png|caption=Postcard Attachment #1}}
<div class="log-content">
As I passed on through the signs written in English, cleanly carved above crude scratches of geometric symbols and shapes, the lights bloomed on afar; the warm color contrasted the serene turquoise etched into the skyline, as mountains and buildings disappeared behind the veils of distant, short fog. The waters lightly, and reassuringly crashed into the shore; the crashing invited me—embraced me—to look beyond—to gaze at the human-made buildings meant to be miles behind me, yet in front of my eyes.

I walked down the pathway of crooked stone, haphazardly aligned in patterns; unpolished—I could feel the edges of my shoes lightly bend around the curves as the shore thrashed. I could see the sky's infinite eyes awake at once from my right, and I could see–I could feel a pack of glowing eyes observing and monitoring me from the darkness beyond; eyes looking on with curiosity.

And as I reached the bottom of the road, I could feel the water shiver through the earth. The cold, wooden fence gate leading down to the coast creaked as I opened it; that creaking lightly reverberated through the landscape; and finally, here I was, just in time to see the glowing fractures in the sky, fractures topped by eyes that pierced through the idyllic green. I could see the Ruphan flags wave from the other side as the muffled, distant cheering found its way to me.

I see the eyes glisten; I see them shine, sparkle, and parade; they dance around the fractures as the water kisses my shoes. I hope her mind is at peace, and I hope mine is too after what I did.
</div>
