</div>
<br>
{{Template:Blurimage|file=L-100 Seawalkers.png|caption=A photograph of 2 Seawalkers observing the shore.}}
With appendages stuck deep below water—appendages lightly touching the seabed—they slowly wander, observe, and look after the humans below. Their dark, spindly body viscerally weakened, limbs that produce an almost knuckle-crack-like sound with every minute movement, each crack more liquid-y than the last, each crack's size echoing through the surroundings. Their constant frown shines a glowing cyan; their constant frown pierces through fog and lights up the most pitch-black void. They don't intend to harm but rather to understand; they don't exist to intimidate but to learn what living means. They're a tulpae-ified species, a Florist manifestation symbolic of human discovery, as well as a metaphor for sapience and its undying courage to understand what the self truly means. 

Despite being naturally harmless, Seawalkers participate in self-defense if necessary, using their strong limbs to knock anyone up and into the air, resulting in hunting being ill-advised regardless of equipment. However, this hasn't stopped them from becoming a common target for smaller raiders and major groups alike: their grand stature and fully fleshy body devoid of bones, their flesh with meager taste yet incredible nutrition—each aspect makes them ideal victims for a hunt; as well as that, a singular Seawalker can feed up to 10 people in one feast. Their frowns are quite sought after as well, primarily by scientific groups such as the [[Entity Research Committee|E.R.C.]] and Kastenie, a result of their composition: solid, single-celled, freely deformable, bioluminescent solids with the ability to be infected by viruses for Medicare testing and to produce bouts of nutritious algae when consuming proteins in water.

Many advocate letting their existence simmer, letting their tulpaeic radiation wear off, to let them fully integrate with the Wake and become part of [[The Hive]], similar to the fate of [[Entity 5|Clumps]], and while this advocacy has majorly helped in establishing regulations within most groups, individual hunters are infrequently held accountable in uncontrolled territory, leading to Seawalkers being on the brink of extinction. An estimated 82 are still alive as of 2002.

=== Callers ===
