==Extra Information==
===Suburbian English===
{{Template:Blurimage|file=FTS-Suburbian-Flag.png|caption=The Suburbian flag as officially designed by the SNC. It's widely used as a civil ensign.}}
It's important for foreigners within the level to be aware of the cultural differences of "Suburbians"—the generic, regional demonym for native inhabitants—the most noticeable of which being Suburbian English, the local dialect originating from the late 19th century. It sports several accentual differences—stretching of long vowels and clipping of shorter ones, leisurely, relaxed speech, emphasized syllables, staccato-timed speech rhythm, dropped endings, and so on—as well as new slang and smaller grammatical changes. While influences from Ncipetherazi are clear, it's common for wanderers to compare many of the dialect's facets to the "Southern American" accent.

As mentioned, the dialect houses a myriad of new slang; however, for simple stop-bys and visits, you're likely to only hear a few, such as:
* Qutzgoat (''Pronunciation: Kwuh-tz-goat'') - [Suck-up, lapdog]
* Junct (''Pronunciation: Junk-t'') - [Complete idiot, utmost moronic]
* Carove (''Pronunciation: Ke-rove'') - [Massive problem, urgent]
* Kwash (''Pronunciation: Kwash'') - [Child-like antics, highly immature]
* Sarne (''Pronunciation: Sarn'') - [Tired but needing to do something]
* Faroc (''Pronunciation: Fah-rick'') - [Utmost insane, troglodyte]
* Khofner (''Pronunciation: Khof-nurr'') - [Animal with fur]
* Eadrom (''Pronunciation: Ee-drom'') - [Lighter night, equivalent to day in Suburbia]
* Lache (''Pronunciation: Lach''] - [A full eadrom/night cycle, occasionally used outside Suburbia for full day/night cycles]

By far the most intriguing change in Suburbian English is its focus on contractions—the dialect is practically swarmed with this stuff; examples of them being:
* Of -> 'f
* And -> 'n
* Our -> 'r
* You -> 'y
Interestingly, contractions are boundless—they're used both formally and informally; they're stackable; they're used everywhere on any word (for example, <code>tools've</code>, or <code>losses've</code>); they're like [[Entity 8|Hound Syndrome]]—ruthless and all-consuming. In fact, contractions are such a commonly used tool that, not only has it spread to outsiders' jokes, but Suburbians also frequently overplay them to comical extents when around others.

There also exists a new swath of end punctuation, mostly derivatives of the exclamation and question marks:
* ⸮ (irony, loaned from Ncipetherazi)
* ‽ (bewilderment, loaned from Ncipetherazi)
* * (uncertainty)
* ¡ (call-out)

To indicate that someone/something is of some descent, or of some property, it's common for Suburbians to apply the suffix "is" which is then moved to precede the other word:
* of Rupha -> Ruph'''is''' - [<code>Proletarium of Rupha</code> -> <code>Ruphis Proletarium</code>]
* of Suburbian -> Suburb'''is''' - [<code>English of Suburbians</code> -> <code>Suburbis English</code>]
* of Gold -> Gold'''is''' - [<code>Heart of Gold</code> -> <code>Goldis Heart</code>]
* of God -> God'''is''' - [<code>The Broken Firebrand of God</code> -> <code>Godis Broken Firebrand</code>]

And ''finally'', when there are multiple words following the "of"—such as the name of a government department—it's commonplace for the suffix "ye" to be appended onto the last word of that pair and then moved in front of the word with the "is" suffix.
* Department of Science and Technology -> Sciencis'n Technologye Department
* Advocates of Khofner Rights -> Khofneris Rightsye Advocates
* Collective of Suburbian Nations -> Suburbis Nationsye Collective 

